04678nam a22006855i 9781477303160DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211982txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814773031607 a10.7560/7804392doi  a(DE-B1597)588656  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aLIT0060002bisacsh04a401.4121904aThe Prague School :bSelected Writings, 1929-1946 /ced. by Peter Steiner. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1982  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTo Enter the Circle -- tTheses Presented to the First Congress of Slavic Philologists in Prague, 1929. The Prague Linguistic Circle -- tFolklore as a Special Form of Creativity -- tThe Asymmetric Dualism of the Linguistic Sign -- tA Contribution to the Study of Theatrical Signs -- tStructuralism in Esthetics and in Literary Studies -- tThe Semantic Analysis of Philosophical Texts -- tThe Concretization of the Literary Work -- tRitual and Theater -- tThe Roots of Structuralist Esthetics0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Prague Linguistic Circle came into being on the afternoon of October 6, 1926, when five Czech and Russian linguists gathered to hear a lecture by a German colleague. From this international beginning, the interests of the group grew to first encompass language in all its functional heterogeneity and then finally all of culture, which the Circle conceived of as a structure of sign systems. Semiotics was thus the overarching discipline for the Prague School, serving to organize all phenomena shared and exchanged by a cultural community. In recent years increasing attention has been paid to the importance of the Prague School, but writing about it has frequently been marred by misconceptions. The central aim of this volume is to correct those misconceptions and to present the diversity of interests within the Prague School—literary criticism, linguistics, theory of theater, folklore, and philosophy. These essays by Bogatyrëv, Jakobson, Karcevskij, Mukařovský, Rieger, Vodička, and Honzl are here translated into English for the first time. Some have a special historical value in illuminating critical stages of structuralist thinking; others reveal the timeliness of the School's contributions for the theoretical conflicts of our day. Each essay is accompanied by an informative introductory note, and the whole is followed by the editor's "Postscript," tracing the roots of structuralist aesthetics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh1 aBogatyrëv, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHonzl, Jindřich, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJakobson, Roman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarcevskij, Sergej, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMukařovský, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRieger, Ladislav, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSteiner, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSteiner, Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aVodička, Felix, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/78043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477303160423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477303160/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK